   =20
 =20

For a long time, Warren Buffett has been my go-to illustration of the princ=
iple that you are allowed to insider trade on your=C2=A0own=C2=A0inside inf=
ormation. Like:
=09Warren Buffett runs Berkshire Hathaway Inc. and makes=C2=A0its investing=
 decisions.
  [5]

=09When Berkshire Hathaway announces a big position in some company, the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s stock often goes up, because the Warren Buffett seal of app=
roval is very valuable.=09Therefore, when Buffett decides to buy a bunch of=
 stock in some company, he has=C2=A0material nonpublic information=C2=A0abo=
ut that company: He knows that he is buying it, and that the stock will go =
up when people find out.=09Nonetheless, Berkshire Hathaway is=C2=A0allowed=
=C2=A0to buy stock in the company=C2=A0before=C2=A0it announces the positio=
n: It can buy stock first and then say =E2=80=9Chey we bought stock,=E2=80=
=9D rather than announcing =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re gonna buy stock=E2=80=
=9D and then buying it.
  [6]



Insider trading, I   like to   say, is not about=C2=A0fairness; it=E2=80=99=
s about=C2=A0theft. There is not a=C2=A0level playing field=C2=A0for you an=
d Buffett: When Buffett buys stock, he knows something you don=E2=80=99t. I=
t=E2=80=99s just that the secret thing he knows is=C2=A0about himself, so h=
e=E2=80=99s allowed to use it in his trading.
This is all a bit imprecise, though. Warren Buffett is closely identified w=
ith Berkshire Hathaway, but he is not actually Berkshire Hathaway. Berkshir=
e Hathaway is a big public company; Buffett is an employee of the company (=
its chief executive officer) and  owns about 15.6% of its stock. When I cas=
ually say things like =E2=80=9CWarren Buffett can buy some company=E2=80=99=
s stock while knowing that he is buying it,=E2=80=9D I mean =E2=80=9CWarren=
 Buffett can cause Berkshire Hathaway to buy some company=E2=80=99s stock w=
hile knowing that he=E2=80=99s doing that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But the information does not really belong to=C2=A0him; the information is =
not really=C2=A0about himself. The information belongs to=C2=A0Berkshire Ha=
thaway; it is information about=C2=A0Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s=C2=A0buyi=
ng. Though the interaction is complex: Stocks go up when Berkshire Hathaway=
 buys them because Buffett,=C2=A0himself, is the Oracle of Omaha; people fo=
llow Buffett=E2=80=99s decisions, not Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s. In some=
 sense the information he has really is=C2=A0about himself; it=E2=80=99s ju=
st that he works for Berkshire Hathaway and has sort of licensed the inform=
ation to the company.
  [7]
=C2=A0It would be at least awkward for him to buy a stock in his=C2=A0perso=
nal account, knowing that he was then going to buy it for Berkshire Hathawa=
y. He would be trading while in possession of material nonpublic informatio=
n (his decision to buy the stock for Berkshire Hathaway) that he=C2=A0creat=
ed=C2=A0(he made the decision) but that he does not=C2=A0own=C2=A0(the deci=
sion is Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s).
This is a bit clearer in the case of=C2=A0other=C2=A0Berkshire Hathaway emp=
loyees. If you work for Warren Buffett at Berkshire Hathaway and he=E2=80=
=99s like =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m gonna buy a big chunk of  Amalgamated Spats =
after lunch today,=E2=80=9D and you run to your Robinhood account and buy 1=
00 shares for yourself, that=E2=80=99s obviously bad. In fact one of Buffet=
t=E2=80=99s former=C2=A0deputies, David Sokol,=C2=A0infamously bought=C2=A0=
Lubrizol Corp. stock in his personal account before Berkshire acquired the =
company; he was never charged with insider trading,
  [8]
=C2=A0but Buffett  was mad at him.=C2=A0
But in theory this=C2=A0is also more or less true of Buffett: If you=C2=A0a=
re=C2=A0Warren Buffett, and you think to yourself =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m gonn=
a buy a big chunk of Amalgamated Spats after lunch today, in the Berkshire =
account,=E2=80=9D and then you buy a small chunk of it in your personal acc=
ount before lunch, that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know, awkw=
ard? Does Berkshire Hathaway own this information, and are you misusing it?=
 What if you haven=E2=80=99t told anyone about your plans yet? What if you =
are like =E2=80=9Cthere is a 75% chance that I=E2=80=99m gonna buy this sto=
ck for Berkshire after lunch today,=E2=80=9D can you buy it for yourself be=
fore lunch?=C2=A0
Anyway Warren Buffett does actually trade stock in his personal account, an=
d  here=E2=80=99s a ProPublica report finding that he occasionally overlaps=
 a bit with Berkshire Hathaway:

On at least three occasions, Buffett has traded stocks in his personal acco=
unt in the same quarter or the quarter before Berkshire bought or sold shar=
es of the same companies, doing so before the conglomerate=E2=80=99s moves =
were disclosed to the public.
These trades may violate Berkshire=E2=80=99s ethics policies, authored by B=
uffett himself, which require =E2=80=9Call actual and anticipated securitie=
s transactions of Berkshire=E2=80=9D be publicly disclosed before Berkshire=
