      IPOs
   =20
 =20

The basic tactical approach to doing an initial public offering is that you=
 go out and market the company to investors and you try to get orders for m=
ore shares than you have to sell. If you are selling 10 million shares, you=
 want investors to want to buy 20 million. Then you price the IPO (at a pri=
ce where investors would buy 20 million shares) and allocate it to investor=
s. Some investors get all the shares they asked for, some get less, and on =
average they get about 50% of what they wanted.
Then, the next day, the stock opens for trading, and all the people who got=
 fewer shares than they wanted say =E2=80=9Cboy, great company, I wanted 10=
0,000 shares but only got 50,000, so I=E2=80=99m gonna go out and buy the o=
ther 50,000 in the market today.=E2=80=9D So there is buying demand for the=
 shares. Meanwhile some of the people you sold to are flippers; you gave th=
em 100,000 shares and they immediately dump them, creating supply. But on a=
verage there is more demand than supply (you sold fewer shares than people =
wanted), so the price goes up. This is an =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D and is =
mostly considered good, though that is a bit complicated and if the IPO pop=
 is too big =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the stock doubles on the first day =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then   Bill Gurley will show up=C2=A0and complain that the company le=
ft money on the table.=C2=A0
My numbers above were hypothetical, and in fact you will regularly read abo=
ut IPOs that are not two times =E2=80=9Ccovered=E2=80=9D (10 million shares=
 for sale, orders for 20 million) but, like, 10 or 20 times (orders for 100=
 million or 200 million shares). Part of this is fake, though. Investors un=
derstand that this is the game, so if they want 100,000 shares they will pu=
t in an order for 200,000, expecting you to cut them back by 50%, and every=
thing escalates from there. Also the divide between long-term investors who=
 think the company is attractive at the IPO price, and flippers who want to=
 sell into the IPO pop, is shifting and uncertain: Some investors who said =
they were in for the long term, and might even have meant it, will sell on =
the first day of trading if the stock price gets too high (quick profit!) o=
r too low (we made a mistake about this company!).=C2=A0
The bigger=C2=A0tactical problem, though, is that sometimes you will have a=
n IPO with 10 million shares for sale and get orders for, like, 5 million s=
hares, or zero. Sometimes the market is bad, or investors don=E2=80=99t lik=
e the company, or they don=E2=80=99t like the price that you marketed. And =
then the banks have to go back to the company and say =E2=80=9Cuh we have t=
o lower the price range=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cuh maybe let=E2=80=99s delay t=
his IPO=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cuh maybe you should not be a public company af=
ter all.=E2=80=9D This is terrible, for the company, and also for the banks=
, who look bad in front of both their issuer client and their investor cust=
omers.=C2=A0
And so, particularly=C2=A0in choppy IPO markets or with risky deals, banks =
will do things to mitigate this risk. Often that means getting anchor inves=
tors: Before you publicly announce the IPO, you call up a handful of big in=
vestors and try to get them to commit to the deal. The anchor investors pro=
vide some certainty to the IPO (they promise in advance to buy a big chunk =
of shares), and in exchange they get some certainty about allocation (the c=
ompany promises to give them those shares).
In some sense this should make the IPO pop=C2=A0bigger:=C2=A0If you allocat=
e half the deal to anchor investors who plan to hold for the long term and =
who get entirely filled on their orders, then you can allocate fewer shares=
 to flippers, and you can give other, smaller investors fewer shares than t=
hey want, forcing them to go out into the market and buy more shares the ne=
xt day.
But at The Information,  Cory Weinberg reports that banks took this a bit t=
oo far this year:

It seemed like a surefire way to juice investor demand in a tough market: I=
nstacart lined up a group of existing and new investors, ranging from Sequo=
ia Capital to Norway=E2=80=99s sovereign wealth fund, to buy up to $400 mil=
lion, or 60% of the stock it planned to sell in its September initial publi=
c offering. In the days leading up to the IPO, bankers working on it told i=
nvestors they had 23 times more orders for stock than there were shares ava=
ilable.
And yet Instacart dropped below its IPO price just a week into its long-awa=
ited life as a public company. ...
Some of the criticism has centered on one of the most delicate parts of the=
 IPO process: which mutual funds, asset managers and hedge funds get to buy=
 stock in the offering. For Instacart, Birkenstock and software firm Klaviy=
o, bankers allocated most shares across a relatively small set of investors=
 in the deals, according to people briefed on the allocation process. =E2=
=80=A6
That meant there wasn=E2=80=99t enough stock to go around in the IPO for sm=
aller investors that would otherwise look to buy more stock after it begins=
 trading, according to several investors and bankers who work on tech deals=
. =E2=80=A6
Alex Wellins, co-founder and managing partner of investor relations advisor=
y firm The Blueshirt Group, said he has heard =E2=80=9Cunanticipated pushba=
ck=E2=80=9D regarding the heavy use of cornerstone investors in recent deal=
s from a few funds. =E2=80=9CAn unintended negative consequence of that is =
that some investors feel that they can=E2=80=99t get a meaningful enough al=
location, so they are waiting to see how things trade before making a move,=
=E2=80=9D Wellins said. =E2=80=A6
One fund manager whose firm was allotted a small number of shares in the In=
stacart IPO compared investment managers=E2=80=99 lack of interest in buyin=
g stock after the listing to a =E2=80=9Cbuyers=E2=80=99 strike=E2=80=9D aft=
er larger investors that earned big pre-commitments crowded them out. Small=
er shareholders didn=E2=80=99t have big enough stakes in Instacart to keep =
buying once the price started going down, he said.

If you want $50 million of an IPO=C2=A0and get $25 million, you might buy t=
he rest in the secondary market the next day. If you want $50 million and g=
et $2 million, you might be like =E2=80=9Cehh this is not worth bothering w=
ith=E2=80=9D and sell your allocation the next day.

