<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Adam Neumann (2)</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the Wall Street Journal, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3Nq=
LmNvbS9yZWFsLWVzdGF0ZS9jb21tZXJjaWFsL2EtcG9zc2libGUtd2lubmVyLWZyb20td2V3b3J=
rcy10cm91Ymxlcy1hZGFtLW5ldW1hbm4tMDE0NGQwMTg_cmVmbGluaz1pbnRlZ3JhdGVkd2Vidm=
lld19zaGFyZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc8311c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Eliot Brown report=
s</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, with WeWork in bankruptcy and his remaini=
ng shares near worthless, there is a potential for further financial gain f=
or Neumann worth hundreds of millions of dollars.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late 2019, SoftBank=C2=A0committed billions=
 of dollars to bail out WeWork after the office company=E2=80=99s failed at=
tempt at an initial public offering left it low on cash and heavy on losses=
. Neumann was ousted by the company=E2=80=99s board, but before he surrende=
red control of the company he founded, Neumann negotiated significant conce=
ssions and payments from SoftBank.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One concession was a roughly $430 million loan=
 from SoftBank to Neumann that had a key feature: Neumann wasn=E2=80=99t pe=
rsonally on the hook for paying it back. Instead, if he stopped paying, Sof=
tBank would be able to seize his shares in WeWork as collateral.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The value of that collateral has plummeted. Wi=
th WeWork=E2=80=99s stock price near zero, Neumann=E2=80=99s WeWork shares =
are currently worth $4 million, down from around $500 million in fall 2021,=
 according to FactSet. SoftBank executives worry that Neumann may elect to =
simply walk away with the money he was lent and hand over the shares, peopl=
e familiar with the situation said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">YOU THINK? Imagine if he didn=E2=80=99t! Imagi=
ne if he walked into SoftBank=E2=80=99s offices and was like =E2=80=9Chey I=
 know that I don=E2=80=99t technically owe you any money, but you=E2=80=99v=
e had a rough time lately and I=E2=80=99m doing pretty well for myself, so =
here=E2=80=99s a few hundred million dollars just as a gift from me to you.=
=E2=80=9D Has anything remotely like that ever happened in the whole histor=
y of WeWork? No, no, only the reverse has happened:=C2=A0<em>SoftBank=C2=A0=
</em>has given <em>Neumann</em>=C2=A0gobs of money for no obvious reason, o=
ver and over again, including this sweet loan. Now he has the choice to pay=
 back a nine-digit loan with either (1) actual money or (2) shares of a ban=
krupt company. He would be crazy to pay with money. And not crazy in way th=
at impressed Masayoshi Son all those years ago.=C2=A0Bad crazy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way,=C2=A0I would not really describe t=
his transaction as, like, =E2=80=9CSoftBank loaned Neumann some money and n=
ow they worry that he=E2=80=99s not gonna pay them back.=E2=80=9D I would a=
nalyze this transaction more as =E2=80=9CSoftBank=C2=A0<em>bought=C2=A0</em=
>$430 million of stock from Neumann when they kicked him out, but with some=
 schmuck insurance on both sides=E2=80=9D:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It <em>looks bad</em>, for WeWork (an=
d its owner SoftBank), to have its founder dump all that stock on his way o=
ut the door, so if you=C2=A0<em>call=C2=A0</em>it a loan you save a bit of =
face. You can say that Neumann is still a big shareholder, even though he h=
as gotten cash for his shares.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If =
somehow WeWork instantly recovered from the failed IPO debacle=C2=A0and bec=
ame a $90 billion company, Neumann would be pretty bummed about selling at =
the bottom.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you do it as a loan payable in stock: Neuma=
nn technically still owns the stock, he gets cash for it up front, if the c=
ompany craters he keeps the cash, but if the company soars he keeps the sto=
ck. It=E2=80=99s a big cash payoff plus some stock options. The options tur=
ned out to be worthless, but the cash is still good.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Warren Buffett</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a long time, Warren Buffett has been my go=
-to illustration of the principle that you are allowed to insider trade on =
your=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>inside information. Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Warren Buffett runs Berkshire Hathawa=
y Inc. and makes=C2=A0its investing decisions.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When Berkshire Hathaway announces=
 a big position in some company, the company=E2=80=99s stock often goes up,=
 because the Warren Buffett seal of approval is very valuable.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, when Buffett decides to buy a bunch=
 of stock in some company, he has=C2=A0<em>material nonpublic information=
=C2=A0</em>about that company: He knows that he is buying it, and that the =
stock will go up when people find out.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Nonetheless, Berkshire Hathaway is=C2=A0<em>allowed=C2=A0</em>to buy s=
tock in the company=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em>it announces the position: It=
 can buy stock first and then say =E2=80=9Chey we bought stock,=E2=80=9D ra=
ther than announcing =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re gonna buy stock=E2=80=9D an=
d then buying it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Insider trading, I <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMTMveW91LWhhdmUtdG8tcGF5LXRoZS1yaWdo=
dC1wZXJzb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1413da8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  like</a> to <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDIvZG9uLXQtaW5zaWRlci10=
cmFkZS1uZnRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXR=
tX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdH=
VmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc1a82718" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  say</a>, is not about=C2=
=A0<em>fairness</em>; it=E2=80=99s about=C2=A0<em>theft</em>. There is not =
a=C2=A0<em>level playing field=C2=A0</em>for you and Buffett: When Buffett =
buys stock, he knows something you don=E2=80=99t. It=E2=80=99s just that th=
e secret thing he knows is=C2=A0<em>about himself</em>, so he=E2=80=99s all=
owed to use it in his trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all a bit imprecise, though. Warren Bu=
ffett is closely identified with Berkshire Hathaway, but he is not actually=
 Berkshire Hathaway. Berkshire Hathaway is a big public company; Buffett is=
 an employee of the company (its chief executive officer) and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTA2Nzk4My8wMDAxMTkzMTI1Mj=
MwNzM5NDgvZDM2MjQzNmRkZWYxNGEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfc8ba50" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> owns about 15.6%</a> of its stock. When I casually say things like =E2=
=80=9CWarren Buffett can buy some company=E2=80=99s stock while knowing tha=
t he is buying it,=E2=80=9D I mean =E2=80=9CWarren Buffett can cause Berksh=
ire Hathaway to buy some company=E2=80=99s stock while knowing that he=E2=
=80=99s doing that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the information does not really belong to=
=C2=A0<em>him</em>; the information is not really=C2=A0<em>about himself</e=
m>. The information belongs to=C2=A0<em>Berkshire Hathaway</em>; it is info=
rmation about=C2=A0<em>Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>buying. Thoug=
h the interaction is complex: Stocks go up when Berkshire Hathaway buys the=
m because Buffett,=C2=A0<em>himself</em>, is the Oracle of Omaha; people fo=
llow <em>Buffett=E2=80=99s</em> decisions, not Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s=
. In some sense the information he has really is=C2=A0<em>about himself</em=
>; it=E2=80=99s just that he works for Berkshire Hathaway and has sort of l=
icensed the information to the company.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It would be at least awkward for him to buy a stock in his=C2=A0<=
em>personal account</em>, knowing that he was then going to buy it for Berk=
shire Hathaway. He would be trading while in possession of material nonpubl=
ic information (his decision to buy the stock for Berkshire Hathaway) that =
he=C2=A0<em>created=C2=A0</em>(he made the decision) but that he does not=
=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>(the decision is Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a bit clearer in the case of=C2=A0<em>=
other=C2=A0</em>Berkshire Hathaway employees. If you work for Warren Buffet=
t at Berkshire Hathaway and he=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m gonna bu=
y a big chunk of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
3314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TaW1wc29uc1FPVEQvc3RhdHVzLzEyNDUz=
MTU2ODQ0NTM4MTQyNzM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0b05f46" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Amalgamated=
 Spats</a> after lunch today,=E2=80=9D and you run to your Robinhood accoun=
t and buy 100 shares for yourself, that=E2=80=99s obviously bad. In fact on=
e of Buffett=E2=80=99s former=C2=A0deputies, David Sokol,=C2=A0infamously b=
ought=C2=A0Lubrizol Corp. stock in his personal account before Berkshire ac=
quired the company; he was never <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZS91=
cy1zb2tvbC1iZXJrc2hpcmVoYXRoYXdheS9zZWMtZHJvcHMtY2FzZS1hZ2FpbnN0LWV4LWJlcmt=
zaGlyZS1leGVjLXNva29sLWxhd3llci1pZFVTQlJFOTAzMDQ1MjAxMzAxMDQ/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB62464df0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">charged with insider trading</a>,<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but Buffett <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9zb2tvbC1sdWJ=
yaXpvbC1iZXJrc2hpcmUtYnVmZmV0dC12aW9sYXRlZC1jb21wYW55LWluc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy=
1wb2xpY3ktMjAxMS00/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB561e797d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> was mad at h=
im</a>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in theory this=C2=A0is also more or less t=
rue of Buffett: If you=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>Warren Buffett, and you think=
 to yourself =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m gonna buy a big chunk of Amalgamated Spat=
s after lunch today, in the Berkshire account,=E2=80=9D and then you buy a =
small chunk of it in your personal account before lunch, that=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know, awkward? Does Berkshire Hathaway own this=
 information, and are you misusing it? What if you haven=E2=80=99t told any=
one about your plans yet? What if you are like =E2=80=9Cthere is a 75% chan=
ce that I=E2=80=99m gonna buy this stock for Berkshire after lunch today,=
=E2=80=9D can you buy it for yourself before lunch?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Warren Buffett does actually trade stoc=
k in his personal account, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvcHVibGljYS5vcmcvYXJ0aWNsZS=
93YXJyZW4tYnVmZmV0dC1wcml2YXRlbHktdHJhZGVkLXN0b2Nrcy1iZXJrc2hpcmUtaGF0aGF3Y=
XktZXRoaWNzLWlycw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfed71447" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99=
s a ProPublica report</a> finding that he occasionally overlaps a bit with =
Berkshire Hathaway:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On at least three occasions, Buffett has trade=
d stocks in his personal account in the same quarter or the quarter before =
Berkshire bought or sold shares of the same companies, doing so before the =
conglomerate=E2=80=99s moves were disclosed to the public.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These trades may violate Berkshire=E2=80=99s e=
thics policies, authored by Buffett himself, which require =E2=80=9Call act=
ual and anticipated securities transactions of Berkshire=E2=80=9D be public=
ly disclosed before Berkshire employees can trade the stocks personally.</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The data here is slim: ProPublica has some tax=
 forms, which report Buffett=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>sales=C2=A0</em>but not his=
 <em>purchases</em>, so there are no findings like =E2=80=9Che bought a sto=
ck a week before Berkshire Hathaway did.=E2=80=9D Sometimes he=C2=A0<em>sol=
d=C2=A0</em>stock around the same time that Berkshire did. Other times, he =
sold stock around the same time that Berkshire was buying it, which seems l=
ike not a particularly devious or lucrative=C2=A0use of inside information.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general he doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have mad=
e any windfalls from his knowledge of Berkshire=E2=80=99s actions, or done =
anything illegal; if there is a scandal here it is that Buffett has said in=
 public that =E2=80=9Che steers clear of trading stocks that his company is=
 trading,=E2=80=9D but sometimes he doesn=E2=80=99t. Meh.=C2=A0Also that is=
 kind of a weird policy? From ProPublica:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In February 2012, Buffett was asked on CNBC wh=
y, despite his praise of JPMorgan Chase, Berkshire did not invest in the ba=
nk. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll let you in on a little secret,=E2=80=9D Buffett r=
esponded. =E2=80=9CI own some shares of JPMorgan.=E2=80=9D He explained tha=
t because Berkshire didn=E2=80=99t own any shares of the giant bank, =E2=80=
=9Cit=E2=80=99s one that I can buy without having any possible problems abo=
ut conflict.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The question came up a second time at a Berksh=
ire shareholder meeting that year, and Buffett gave almost the same answer.=
 He said he preferred Wells Fargo, but Berkshire was =E2=80=9Cbuying Wells =
Fargo stock and that takes me out of the business of buying Wells Fargo,=E2=
=80=9D so he bought shares of Chase for his personal account because it was=
 his second choice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s one of the problems I =
have,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t be buying what Berkshire i=
s buying and I=E2=80=99ve got some money around and therefore I go into my =
second choices or into tiny little companies.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Really? No possible problems about conflict? J=
PMorgan=E2=80=99s stock=C2=A0has=C2=A0significantly<em>=C2=A0</em>outperfor=
med Wells Fargo=E2=80=99s since February 2012. Warren Buffett, the legendar=
y stock picker, picked two big banks that he liked; he bought one for himse=
lf and one for his shareholders. The one he bought for himself was, he said=
, his second choice, but it performed much better than the one that he boug=
ht for his shareholders. Is that not a conflict of interest? Would it not a=
lign interests a bit if Buffett bought the stocks for himself that he buys =
for his company?</p>
