<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic tactical approach to doing an initia=
l public offering is that you go out and market the company to investors an=
d you try to get orders for more shares than you have to sell. If you are s=
elling 10 million shares, you want investors to want to buy 20 million. The=
n you price the IPO (at a price where investors would buy 20 million shares=
) and allocate it to investors. Some investors get all the shares they aske=
d for, some get less, and on average they get about 50% of what they wanted=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then, the next day, the stock opens for tradin=
g, and all the people who got fewer shares than they wanted say =E2=80=9Cbo=
y, great company, I wanted 100,000 shares but only got 50,000, so I=E2=80=
=99m gonna go out and buy the other 50,000 in the market today.=E2=80=9D So=
 there is buying demand for the shares. Meanwhile some of the people you so=
ld to are flippers; you gave them 100,000 shares and they immediately dump =
them, creating supply. But on average there is more demand than supply (you=
 sold fewer shares than people wanted), so the price goes up. This is an =
=E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D and is mostly considered good, though that is a b=
it complicated and if the IPO pop is too big =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the stock do=
ubles on the first day =E2=80=94=C2=A0then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDcvdGhlLWlwby1tYXJrZXQtd2FzLXRvby1nb29kP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB859fb486" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bill Gurley will show up</a>=C2=A0and =
complain that the company left money on the table.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My numbers above were hypothetical, and in fac=
t you will regularly read about IPOs that are not two times =E2=80=9Ccovere=
d=E2=80=9D (10 million shares for sale, orders for 20 million) but, like, 1=
0 or 20 times (orders for 100 million or 200 million shares). Part of this =
is fake, though. Investors understand that this is the game, so if they wan=
t 100,000 shares they will put in an order for 200,000, expecting you to cu=
t them back by 50%, and everything escalates from there. Also the divide be=
tween long-term investors who think the company is attractive at the IPO pr=
ice, and flippers who want to sell into the IPO pop, is shifting and uncert=
ain: Some investors who said they were in for the long term, and might even=
 have meant it, will sell on the first day of trading if the stock price ge=
ts too high (quick profit!) or too low (we made a mistake about this compan=
y!).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bigger=C2=A0tactical problem, though, is t=
hat sometimes you will have an IPO with 10 million shares for sale and get =
orders for, like, 5 million shares, or zero. Sometimes the market is bad, o=
r investors don=E2=80=99t like the company, or they don=E2=80=99t like the =
price that you marketed. And then the banks have to go back to the company =
and say =E2=80=9Cuh we have to lower the price range=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cu=
h maybe let=E2=80=99s delay this IPO=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cuh maybe you shou=
ld not be a public company after all.=E2=80=9D This is terrible, for the co=
mpany, and also for the banks, who look bad in front of both their issuer c=
lient and their investor customers.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so, particularly=C2=A0in choppy IPO market=
s or with risky deals, banks will do things to mitigate this risk. Often th=
at means getting anchor investors: Before you publicly announce the IPO, yo=
u call up a handful of big investors and try to get them to commit to the d=
eal. The anchor investors provide some certainty to the IPO (they promise i=
n advance to buy a big chunk of shares), and in exchange they get some cert=
ainty about allocation (the company promises to give them those shares).</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense this should make the IPO pop=C2=
=A0<em>bigger:=C2=A0</em>If you allocate half the deal to anchor investors =
who plan to hold for the long term and who get entirely filled on their ord=
ers, then you can allocate fewer shares to flippers, and you can give other=
, smaller investors fewer shares than they want, forcing them to go out int=
o the market and buy more shares the next day.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at The Information, <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33314957.258406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlaW5m=
b3JtYXRpb24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL2JhbmtzLXJhbi10aGVpci1zYWZlc3QtaXBvLXBsYXlib29=
rcy10aGlzLXllYXItaW52ZXN0b3JzLXNheS1pdC1iYWNrZmlyZWQ_b2ZmZXI9cnRzdS1lbmdhZ2=
VtZW50LXNlcHQtMjMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVJUU1UrLStCYW5rcytJUE8rUGxhJnV0bV9jb250Z=
W50PTIxNTAmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNpbyZ1dG1fdGVybT0xNTcwJnJj=
PTFiZGk1aA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB154257a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Cory Weinberg report=
s</a> that banks took this a bit too far this year:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seemed like a surefire way to juice investo=
r demand in a tough market: Instacart lined up a group of existing and new =
investors, ranging from Sequoia Capital to Norway=E2=80=99s sovereign wealt=
h fund, to buy up to $400 million, or 60% of the stock it planned to sell i=
n its September initial public offering. In the days leading up to the IPO,=
 bankers working on it told investors they had 23 times more orders for sto=
ck than there were shares available.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet Instacart dropped below its IPO price =
just a week into its long-awaited life as a public company. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the criticism has centered on one of t=
he most delicate parts of the IPO process: which mutual funds, asset manage=
rs and hedge funds get to buy stock in the offering. For Instacart, Birkens=
tock and software firm Klaviyo, bankers allocated most shares across a rela=
tively small set of investors in the deals, according to people briefed on =
the allocation process. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That meant there wasn=E2=80=99t enough stock t=
o go around in the IPO for smaller investors that would otherwise look to b=
uy more stock after it begins trading, according to several investors and b=
ankers who work on tech deals. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alex Wellins, co-founder and managing partner =
of investor relations advisory firm The Blueshirt Group, said he has heard =
=E2=80=9Cunanticipated pushback=E2=80=9D regarding the heavy use of corners=
tone investors in recent deals from a few funds. =E2=80=9CAn unintended neg=
ative consequence of that is that some investors feel that they can=E2=80=
=99t get a meaningful enough allocation, so they are waiting to see how thi=
ngs trade before making a move,=E2=80=9D Wellins said. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One fund manager whose firm was allotted a sma=
ll number of shares in the Instacart IPO compared investment managers=E2=80=
=99 lack of interest in buying stock after the listing to a =E2=80=9Cbuyers=
=E2=80=99 strike=E2=80=9D after larger investors that earned big pre-commit=
ments crowded them out. Smaller shareholders didn=E2=80=99t have big enough=
 stakes in Instacart to keep buying once the price started going down, he s=
aid.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want $50 million of an IPO=C2=A0and get=
 $25 million, you might buy the rest in the secondary market the next day. =
If you want $50 million and get $2 million, you might be like =E2=80=9Cehh =
this is not worth bothering with=E2=80=9D and sell your allocation the next=
 day.</p>
